# Sports community at UCSC

![Candid Carlson: Record-breaking No. 2 UCLA women's basketball ...][image1]

[image1]: <data:image/jpeg;base64,>

Have you ever wondered why the sports scene is not as accessible and pronounced at UC Santa Cruz compared to other colleges? When I think of UC Santa Cruz, my mind doesn't go to sports and there might be some deliberate reasons for that. I often hear online about the lack of a collective student body through sports on campus. This all can be traced back to a past decision to reject the competitive athletic model prevalent at other universities. Instead, it focuses on a decentralized, non-competitive intramural and club sports system that aligned with its founding ethos of individualized learning.   

At UC Santa Cruz, athletics exist, but the scale and structure of its programs contribute to a noticeably smaller sports community compared to many universities. UC Santa Cruz is the only UC competing in National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) Division III UCSC sponsors 15 varsity sports, including mens and womens basketball, soccer, swimming and diving, tennis, volleyball, cross country, track and field, and womens golf. Being a Division III institution comes with some drawbacks like how UCSC does not offer athletic scholarships or give admissions preference to athletes, which tends to draw fewer students seeking high-level, competitive sports programs.  

According to a [university-wide breakdown](https://news.ucsc.edu/2016/04/athletics-faq/?utm_source=chatgpt.com), approximately 280 students less than 2 percent of undergraduates participate in the NCAA program. Around 900 students (about 5.5 percent) play club sports; and roughly 4,000 students (about 23 percent) take part in recreational sports through the universitys recreation program. With the numbers so low, sports often fail to gain widespread visibility or become central to campus social life. This is in contrast to many larger universities like those in the  NCAA Division I who channel considerable funding, marketing, and institutional emphasis into athletics, creating large stadiums, regular media attention, and an ingrained school spirit around games. While UCSC holds occasional athletic successes (for example, [national championships](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UC_Santa_Cruz_Banana_Slugs?utm_source=chatgpt.com) in certain Division III sports by the UC Santa Cruz Banana Slugs), the limited scope of these programs and the lower emphasis on athletic competition make it difficult to replicate a sports-centred campus identity.  

How might the funding be carried out? Well in the 2016-17 fiscal year, UC Santa Cruz's athletics department had a budget of approximately $1.4 million, but its salary and operating costs (expenditures) were around $2 million. This resulted in a deficit, leading to a vote to determine support for a new quarterly fee. Ultimately, the decision was passed to allow the program to continue into the future via a new student fee revenue model. A couple of other ways they receive funding is Philanthropy / Donations / Fundraising gifts, fundraising efforts, alumni or community donations, etc.   

This begs the question, are students getting what they pay for in fees towards the athletics department? According to UCSCs fee breakdown lists, theres a line for Intercoll. Athletics Sports Team Fee at $15/year (i.e. $5 per quarter) and an Intercollegiate Athletics and Athletics Activities Access Fee showing $115.50/year (i.e. $38.50 per quarter) though that larger fee appears in the budget line-items after the proposed referendum in 2017\. When you compare these fees to another UC like UC Irvine, the price gap is very clear. The fees found on [UCI Registrar](https://reg.uci.edu/fees/2025-2026/undergrad_25.html?utm_source=chatgpt.com) are: Campus Spirit Fee: US$99.00 per year (i.e. $33.00 per quarter), Recreation Center Fee: US$264.00 per year (i.e. $88.00 per quarter), Bren Events Center Fee: US$69.00 per year (i.e. $23.00 per quarter), Club Sports Fee: US$21.00 per year (i.e. $7.00 per quarter).   

I don't believe we are not receiving what we pay for, and if you attend UCSC, you may feel the same way. The way that sports are represented in our school may not be like others, but that's on purpose and well-known. [The founding philosophy](https://www.universityofcalifornia.edu/news/uc-santa-cruz-turns-50#:~:text=Modeled%20on%20Oxford%20University%20in,campus's%20first%20chancellor%2C%20in%201966.) of UC Santa Cruz, which emphasized a small, liberal arts college model based on Oxford University, prioritized academics and a close-knit, decentralized student-faculty environment over a large-scale athletic program. The university was established with a unique academic structure that did not include traditional sports facilities or a strong emphasis on athletics. This model, with its cluster of small colleges, was a key part of the original design, influencing the initial lack of sports infrastructure and programming. UCSC may not have a robust sports community, but where it lacks in sports, it makes up for in other areas, and there are plenty of ways to get involved via other school events and communities.
